						<td style="font-size: 14pt; font-weight: bold" colspan="2">
							HealthSouth: Ousted CEO Won't Return
						</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td style="font-size: 11pt;"> 
							 
							<br>
							<br>
							10:35 AM EST May 31, 2003 
							<br>
							The Associated Press<br><br><br>BIRMINGHAM, Ala.<p class="nitfp">A streamlined HealthSouth Corp. is recovering financially and its new leadership will not allow ousted CEO Richard Scrushy back, company officials said in a letter to employees.</p>
<p class="nitfp">The letter filed Friday with the Securities and Exchange Commission was signed by interim chairman Joel C. Gordon and interim chief executive Robert P. May, who took the helm of the health services giant after a massive accounting fraud case was brought against it and Scrushy.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"Our ongoing operations are generating positive cash flow, our cash position continues to improve, and we are meeting our commitments to our employees, suppliers and physician partners," the letter says.</p>
<p class="nitfp">HealthSouth, struggling with $3.3 billion in debt, will develop a restructuring plan.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"Whatever course we take to fix the financial side of our business, in or out of bankruptcy court, we expect - and you should expect - that HealthSouth will continue to operate uninterrupted," the letter says.</p>
<p class="nitfp">As for Scrushy, the letter says, "We do not foresee any circumstance under which he will be welcome again at HealthSouth."</p>
<p class="nitfp">One of Scrushy's lawyers has said he is trying to gather investors to buy the firm, but Gordon and May said those reports were issued to "distract the media from the former CEO's very serious legal situation."</p>
<p class="nitfp">Birmingham businessman Daryl Harms, whose Masada Resources Group is involved in converting garbage into ethanol, has said he is talking with investors about buying HealthSouth.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Harms said he has not had any direct contact with Scrushy, but has discussed his plans with Donald Watkins, the lawyer defending Scrushy against fraud claims.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Watkins said last week he was lining up investors interested in buying the company, and that they would hire Scrushy as an adviser. Harms said he would not rule out Scrushy being involved with the company if his bid succeeds.</p>

